The U.S. Anti-China Technology War
From New York — — The worst diplomatic policy decision made by the previous generation (and even earlier generations) of Americans was the 2003 "War of Choice" launched against Iraq, which claimed to aim at eliminating — — non-existent — — weapons of mass destruction.
Understanding the necessity of the flawed logic behind this catastrophic decision has become more critical than ever, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar U.S. misleading policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-U.S. Vice President Richard Cheney, who claimed that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands was small (e.g., 1%), we should act as if it were certain to happen.
This kind of reasoning almost always leads to wrong decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack Chinese technology.
According to the U.S. government's statement, since we cannot be sure that Chinese technology is safe, we should respond to it by treating it as necessarily harmful and thereby banning it.
The correct decision would apply probability estimates to the various alternative measures.
A generation ago, U.S. policymakers not only had to consider the (claimed) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also had to consider the 99% risk of waging a war based on multiple flawed assumptions.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) distracted the public's attention, leading people to ignore the fact that the Iraq War actually lacked justification and would severely disrupt the political stability of the Middle East and the world.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not only that it takes action based on minor risks without considering the potentially huge costs, but that politicians always stir up fear for some hidden agenda.
This is exactly what American leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks to provoke panic about Chinese tech companies.
The most relevant (but not the only) case is the attack by the U.S. government on the communications technology company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually closing its domestic market to the company and trying to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the U.S. may ultimately cause an unwarranted geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been closely following Huawei's technological progress, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant impetus for eliminating poverty and achieving other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to enhance actions towards the Sustainable Development Goals.
I once wrote a short preface (without payment) for a report that Huawei prepared on this topic, and as a result, I was criticized by those who are hostile towards China. For this, I asked senior industry figures and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had behaved improperly, and the repeated answer I received was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may endanger global security.
American officials claim that "backdoors" retained in Huawei's software or hardware may enable the Chinese government to conduct surveillance worldwide.
They point out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are now clear.
Huawei's 5G equipment is inexpensive and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and beginning to be promoted.
Its high performance comes from huge investments in R&D over the years, economies of scale, and its experience in the Chinese digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology for sustainable development, it would be clearly unwise for low-income economies around the world to delay the rollout of 5G.
However, despite being unable to provide any evidence of backdoors, the United States is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The United States claims its arguments are universal.
As one U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner said: "The country with 5G will have the related innovation and set the standards for other regions of the world, and this country is unlikely to be the United States at the moment."
Other countries — especially the United Kingdom — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they are almost certainly able to be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei in Germany is also intensifying, as the U.S. government threatens to reduce intelligence cooperation unless authorities exclude Huawei's 5G technology.
Perhaps under U.S. pressure, the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a field that should be open to a group that cannot be fully trusted."
But he has not provided any evidence of specific crimes.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been fighting behind the scenes to open the market to Huawei.
Ironically, however, the U.S. complaints partly reflect its own surveillance activities domestically and abroad — although this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment may make it more difficult for the U.S. government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any government's unlawful surveillance activities should be stopped.
The independent oversight by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards rather than engage in a technological battle.
The threatening impact of the U.S. demand to ban Huawei is not limited to the early rollout of 5G networks, but also poses a significant risk to the rule-based trading system.
Now the United States is no longer an undisputed global technological leader, and President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete based on a rule-based system.
Their goal is to curb China's technological rise.
They also attempt to undermine the World Trade Organization by paralyzing its dispute settlement mechanism, which also reflects their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration can "succeed" in dividing the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts will double.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency, expanded the U.S. technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
Part of the reason for the collapse was the protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the 1930 Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act, which exacerbated the Great Depression, contributed to Hitler's rise, and ultimately led to the outbreak of World War II.
As in other areas, in international affairs, being driven by fear and taking action based on that fear — rather than following the evidence — is a path toward self-destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules; this is the safest course of action.
Let us establish independent oversight bodies to reduce the threat of any country using the global network to spy on other countries or launch cyber warfare.
In this way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
